This paper deals with the capacity and delay scaling of wireless networks, which is a topic that falls under the category of computer networks (cs.NI). The paper also makes use of information theory (cs.IT) to derive scaling laws for broadcast capacity and minimum delay. Additionally, the paper discusses the use of Markov Evolving Graphs (MEGs) to analyze the network, which falls under the category of distributed, parallel, and cluster computing (cs.DC). The paper also deals with the optimization of network performance, which falls under the category of social and information networks (cs.SI) and the analysis of large datasets, which falls under the category of data structures and algorithms (cs.DS).
